---
import ContentMedia from '/src/components/ContentMedia.astro'
import FullWidth from '/src/components/FullWidth.astro'
import DefaultLayout from '/src/layouts/DefaultLayout.astro'
import { Link } from 'accessible-astro-components'

//images
import costsImg from '/src/assets/img/costs.png';
import stopwatchImg from '/src/assets/img/stopwatch.png';
import pipelineImg from '/src/assets/img/pipeline.png';
import privacyImg from '/src/assets/img/privacy.png';


---

<DefaultLayout title="Use Cases">
  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <h1>
        Icebreaker Use Cases
      </h1>
    </div>
  </section>
    <section class="mt-8">
        <div class="container">
            <p class="text-2xl">
        Stop running your data lake as a cost center. Run it like a business.
          </p>
        </div>
    </section>

  <FullWidth>
    <p class="text-xl">
     Icebreaker brings provider-grade <strong>serverless economics and automation</strong> to your private data cloud. 
     </p>
    <p class="text-xl">
      By <strong>adapting the compute profile</strong> for every query, Icebreaker can <strong>securely and cost-effectively</strong> deliver millisecond responses for Agentic AI while running high-throughput production pipelines.
    </p>
  </FullWidth>
  <div class="container space-y-0 my-0">
    <section id="agentic-ai">
      <ContentMedia img={costsImg} alt="Expensive" reverseImg={true}>
        <h2>
          Agentic AI Queries
        </h2>
        <p class="text-xl">
          The volume of queries generated by AI Agents is exponentially greater than traditional applications and tend to be more random when it comes to data sources and volume of data being queried.
        </p>
        <p  class="text-xl">
          <strong>Icebreaker Control  </strong>
          With Iceberg catalogs, Icebreaker can quickly source the appropriate tables and Icebreakers controls ensure that queries operate within pre-defined economic parameters.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xl">
            <Link href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.00997" isExternal>
              Read the academic research
            </Link>
        </p>
      </ContentMedia>
    </section>

    <section id="bi-analytics">
      <ContentMedia img={stopwatchImg} alt="Fast">
        <h2>
          Data Analytics | Business Intelligence
        </h2>
        <p class="text-xl">
          BI platforms run repetitive queries against dynamic data tables maintained on expensive, over provisioned cloud databases.  To lower costs data teams will move data to high latency data environments.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xl">
          <strong>Icebreaker Efficiency</strong>  
          Demand Shaping  predicts query execution parameters and aligns resources with infrastructure to create a low latency experience
        </p>
        </ContentMedia>
      </section>

      <section id="etl-elt-pipelines">
        <ContentMedia img={pipelineImg} alt="Pipeline" reverseImg={true}>
        <h2>
          Data Pipelines | ELT | ETL
        </h2>
        <p class="text-xl">
          Today's pipelines are dependent on expensive cloud platform for compute resources that support repetitive, commodity type jobs. 
        </p>
        <p class="text-xl">
          <strong>Icebreaker Private Cloud</strong>  
          Since compute runs in the customer's cloud rather than a cloud platform customers pay for the compute they use, w/o a markup.
        </p>
        </ContentMedia>
      </section>

      <section id="multitenant-oem-saas">
        <ContentMedia img={privacyImg} alt="Private">
        <h2>
          Multi-tenant | OEM | SaaS
        </h2>
        <p class="text-xl">
          While SaaS applications use query engines to deliver insights, reports and analysis, these queries can be classified as commodity/repeatable tasks, that can eat up budget.  
        </p>
        <p class="text-xl">
          <strong>Icebreaker - Costs</strong>  
          By running Icebreaker in your private cloud, your commodity queries can run at a minimum cost to your business.
        </p>
        </ContentMedia>
    </section>
  </div>

</DefaultLayout>
